nulla uirtus prudentia uacat: pru- dentia though usually employed in Cic. (eg. iii 8, 17) as a translation of φρόνησις is here used as equivalent to ἐπιστήμη, scientia, the knowledge which enters into the definition os all virtues (Stob. Ecl. ii 59, 4 W..) Cf. Off. i 43, 153 where the

common to all virtues and the particular virtue prudentia ( φρόνησις) is clearly drawn.

M. Atilio: M.Atilius Regulus, ‘the pro- totype of heroic missortune’ (Mommsen) with the Romans, cons. 256 B.C., defeated and captured by the Carthaginians in 25·, and according to the legend put to death with tortures, cf. Off. iii 26, 99; Hor. C. iii 5, ¹3 sqq, ·.Momrnsen, RH. 11 178ff.

Q. caepione: Q. Servilius Caepio, cos. 106 B.C., defeated by the Cimbri at Arausio in 105, deprived of his office, of his seat in the senate, and of his property, does not seem to have been such a striking example os virtue struggling against missortune as Cicero thinks. Mommsen, RH. 111 436 ff.
